INSERT INTO `pageArchive` VALUES (31, 38, '<h2>Herniated Disc</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><img src="http://spinecenter.kmastage.com/images/uploads/k7854454.jpg" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" />Your spine is made of bones that stack on top of each other.Â  In between each of those bones is a softer cushion.Â  That cushion is called a disc. The disc has a softer center surrounded by a stronger exterior.Â  A herniated disc refers to a problem with your disc where the softer center pushes out through the stronger exterior and can cause pressure or irritation of the nearby nerves.Â  This irritation can result in pain, numbness, tingling and or weakness in the legs. Sometimes a herniated disc causes no symptoms.Â  If you do have symptoms that affect your quality of life then treatment options are available.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Â </h2>\r\n\r\n<h2>Lumbar Radiculopathy</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><img height="145" src="http://spinecenter.kmastage.com/images/uploads/lumbar-radiculopathy.jpg" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" width="91" />Lumbar radiculopathy or sciatica refers to pain that radiates from your back down one or both legs. This pain travels down the path of the sciatic nerve or its branches. The sciatic nerve is the largest nerve in the body and supplies function to the legs. The pain associated with sciatica is related to compression or irritation of one or more nerves from your lower back. This is usually the result of another problem, for example a herniated disc.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<span style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 13px;">DegenerativeÂ </span><span style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 13px;">Disc</span><span style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 13px;">Â Disease /Â </span>Spondylosis</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>DegenerativeÂ discÂ disease refers to the normal aging process to theÂ discÂ or spine.Â  YourÂ discÂ is normally fluid filled in the center and over a period of time thisÂ discÂ will become dehydrated.Â  These changes may or may not cause symptoms.Â  If you have pain related to a degenerativeÂ discÂ it usually causes lower back pain that canÂ  range from mild to severe.Â  Even though you may have changes seen byÂ xrayÂ or MRI it doesnâ€™t mean you will have pain or that the pain will be permanent.Â Â Â </p>\r\n\r\n<p>SpondylosisÂ is the normal aging process to the bones in the spine.Â  Another term forÂ spondylosisÂ is osteoarthritis of the spine.Â  It affects the spinal bones and joints rather than theÂ discsÂ of the spine.Â  It also can cause lower back pain that can range from mild to severe.Â  Treatment options depend on the severity of the symptoms associated with the arthritis.Â Â Â Â </p>\r\n\r\n<p>DegenerativeÂ DiscÂ Disease andÂ spondylosisÂ are both considered to be normal wear and tear changes to the spine.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>LumbarÂ Stenosis</h2>\r\n\r\n<p><img align="left" height="160" src="/images/lumbar-stenosis.jpg" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt;" />Lumbar or spinalÂ stenosisÂ is a narrowing of the canal where your nerves are held in your lower back.Â  This narrowing is usually a result ofÂ discÂ bulging andÂ spondylosisÂ (osteoarthritis) of the spinal joints.Â  If the nerves are compressed this can cause nerve pain shooting into the legs.Â  This pain can be associated with numbness, tingling, weakness, and rarely bowel and bladder dysfunction.Â  The pain is usually worse with walking and can get better with leaning forward and sitting down.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2><br />\r\n<br />\r\nCervical Disc Herniation</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>A cervical disc is a round, flatÂ  cushion between each of the verterbrae (bones) in the spine.Â  They act as shock absorbers for theÂ  spine.Â  A disc that bulges out of placeÂ  or breaks open is a bulging or herniated disc.Â </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Cervical Radiculopathy</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Damage or irritation to one or more of the nerves exiting off the spinalÂ  cord resulting in symptoms of pain, numbness, tingling, and/or weakness in aÂ  shoulder or arm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Cervical Stenosis/Myelopathy</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Cervical stenosis is a narrowing of the spinalÂ  canal. This is normally a slow, gradual process.Â  This can lead to narrowing or squeezing ofÂ  the nerves exiting the spinal cord or actually irritate or press on the spinalÂ  cord itself.Â  Cervical myelopathy is aÂ  compression of the spinal cord resulting from stenosis.Â  Symptoms of myelopathy can include heavyÂ  feeling in the legs, gait or balance disturbance, clumsy hands, decrease inÂ  fine motor skills, and bladder or bowel dysfunction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Idiopathic Scoliosis</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Scoliosis refers to a lateralÂ  curvature of the spine.Â  IdiopathicÂ  scoliosis is of unknown cause and may be related to a family history ofÂ  scoliosis.Â  Adolescent IdiopathicÂ  Scoliosis is the more common form and is found between the ages of 10 and 19.Â  It is more common in girls than boys.Â  It can be progressive and it is importantÂ  that the curvature be monitored by a physician.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Adult Scoliosis</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Scoliosis (lateral curvature of the spine) found in individuals greaterÂ  than 19 years of age.Â  Causes includeÂ  idiopathic scoliosis missed in childhood which progressed and becameÂ  symptomactic or other conditions including degenerative disc disease,Â  congenital abnormalities, trauma or fractures, and neuro-muscular diseasesÂ  (post-polio syndrome, muscular dystrophy, etc).</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 13px;">Cervical </span><span style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 13px;">Disc</span><span style="line-height: 1.2; font-size: 13px;"> </span>Herniation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A cervical disc is a round, flatÂ  cushion between each of the verterbrae (bones) in the spine.Â  They act as shock absorbers for theÂ  spine.Â  A disc that bulges out of placeÂ  or breaks open is a bulging or herniated disc.Â </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Cervical Radiculopathy</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Damage or irritation to one or more of the nerves exiting off the spinalÂ  cord resulting in symptoms of pain, numbness, tingling, and/or weakness in aÂ  shoulder or arm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Cervical Stenosis/Myelopathy</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Cervical stenosis is a narrowing of the spinalÂ  canal. This is normally a slow, gradual process.Â  This can lead to narrowing or squeezing ofÂ  the nerves exiting the spinal cord or actually irritate or press on the spinalÂ  cord itself.Â  Cervical myelopathy is aÂ  compression of the spinal cord resulting from stenosis.Â  Symptoms of myelopathy can include heavyÂ  feeling in the legs, gait or balance disturbance, clumsy hands, decrease inÂ  fine motor skills, and bladder or bowel dysfunction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Idiopathic Scoliosis</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Scoliosis refers to a lateralÂ  curvature of the spine.Â  IdiopathicÂ  scoliosis is of unknown cause and may be related to a family history ofÂ  scoliosis.Â  Adolescent IdiopathicÂ  Scoliosis is the more common form and is found between the ages of 10 and 19.Â  It is more common in girls than boys.Â  It can be progressive and it is importantÂ  that the curvature be monitored by a physician.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Adult Scoliosis</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>Scoliosis (lateral curvature of the spine) found in individuals greaterÂ  than 19 years of age.Â  Causes includeÂ  idiopathic scoliosis missed in childhood which progressed and becameÂ  symptomactic or other conditions including degenerative disc disease,Â  congenital abnormalities, trauma or fractures, and neuro-muscular diseasesÂ  (post-polio syndrome, muscular dystrophy, etc).</p>\r\n', '2014-08-29 10:44:08');
