omicon.gif" /></a></div>\r\n\r\n<div id="plugincheck_0909">\r\n<div id="div_plugin_img_player" style="  position: absolute; padding: 12px; left: 50%; top: 50%; visibility:hidden; display:none; z-index:102; vertical-align: middle;">Â </div>\r\n</div>\r\n', '2014-08-29 12:08:08');
INSERT INTO `pageArchive` VALUES (44, 12, '<h2>Scoliosis Corrective Surgery</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This is generally a very complex procedure in which a curved spine is straightened using a variety of correction methods.Â  This is most commonly performed in adolescent patients who have not reached skeletal maturity and have spinal curves that measure greater than 40 degrees.Â  The surgery is performed under general anesthesia and usually involves a long incision down the center of the back to allow for exposure of the curved spine.Â  Special screws and rods are carefully affixed to the spine to allow for gentle straightening and de-rotation.Â  Following surgery, patients stay in the hospital around 3 to 5 days for careful observation, pain control and physical therapy.Â  Patients are braced for approximately 8 weeks following this procedure.</p>\r\n', '2014-08-29 12:12:50');
INSERT INTO `pageArchive` VALUES (45, 12, '<h2>Scoliosis Corrective Surgery</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>This is generally a very complex procedure in which a curved spine is straightened using a variety of correction methods.Â  This is most commonly performed in adolescent patients who have not reached skeletal maturity and have spinal curves that measure greater than 40 degrees.Â  The surgery is performed under general anesthesia and usually involves a long incision down the center of the back to allow for exposure of the curved spine.Â  Special screws and rods are carefully affixed to the spine to allow for gentle straightening and de-rotation.Â  Following surgery, patients stay in the hospital around 3 to 5 days for careful observation, pain control and physical therapy.Â  Patients are braced for approximately 8 weeks following this procedure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Click <a href="https://www.youtube.com/v/mycysi1WM7k?autostart=true" target="_blank">here</a> to read an article posted by one of our physicians, Meegan Domangue, PA-C.</p>\r\n', '2014-08-29 12:13:35');
INSERT INTO `pageArchive` VALUES (46, 14, '<h2>Facet Joint Injection</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The facet joint is where the vertebrae of your spine connect together.Â  If there is arthritis or inflammation surrounding this joint it can be a source of your low back pain. This pain is usually worsened with standing and extension of your lower back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A facet injection is an injection of steroid into the facet joint of the spine. The steroid decreases inflammation in this joint and can relieve pain. Since steroid is used this procedure may provide relief anywhere from weeks to months and in some cases years. These injections can be repeated if needed for continued pain relief.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Risks are rare but include infection, bleeding, prolonged increase in pain, and nerve damage. This procedure is done under X-ray guidance and IV sedation for your comfort.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Epidural Steroid Injection</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>An epidural steroid injection (ESI) is an injection of long lasting steroid (â€œcortisoneâ€) in the epidural space; this space is the area which surrounds the spinal cord and the spinal nerves. The steroid medication injected reduces the inflammation and/or swelling of nerves in the epidural space, which may in turn reduce pain, tingling, numbness, and other symptoms. An ESI may be performed to relieve symptoms that are caused by spinal stenosis, spondylosis, or disc herniation. The procedure is done under IV sedation and with the guidance of an X-ray machine. The actual injection takes only a few minutes to perform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Â </p>\r\n', '2014-08-29 12:25:04');
INSERT INTO `pageArchive` VALUES (47, 14, '<h2>Facet Joint Injection</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>The facet joint is where the vertebrae of your spine connect together.Â  If there is arthritis or inflammation surrounding this joint it can be a source of your low back pain. This pain is usually worsened with standing and extension of your lower back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A facet injection is an injection of steroid into the facet joint of the spine. The steroid decreases inflammation in this joint and can relieve pain. Since steroid is used this procedure may provide relief anywhere from weeks to months and in some cases years. These injections can be repeated if needed for continued pain relief.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Risks are rare but include infection, bleeding, prolonged increase in pain, and nerve damage. This procedure is done under X-ray guidance and IV sedation for your comfort.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Epidural Steroid Injection</h2>\r\n\r\n<p>An epidural steroid injection (ESI) is an injection of long lasting steroid (â€œcortisoneâ€) in the epidural space; this space is the area which surrounds the spinal cord and the spinal nerves. The steroid medication injected reduces the inflammation and/or swelling of nerves in the epidural space, which may in turn reduce pain, tingling, numbness, and other symptoms. An ESI may be performed to relieve symptoms that are caused by spinal stenosis, spondylosis, or disc herniation. The procedure is done under IV sedation and with the guidance of an X-ray machine. The actual injection takes only a few minutes to perform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Click <a href="http://spinecenter.kmastage.com/education-resources/spine-articles/view/spinal-injections/">here</a> to read an article from the American Academy of Orthopedic Surgeons about spinal injections.</p>\r\n', '2014-08-29 12:26:22');
INSERT INTO `pageArchive` VALUES (48, 42, '<p><img align="right" alt="" border="0" hspace="" src="/images/uploads/map.gif" style="margin: 0pt 8px 0pt 15px;" vspace="" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="color: #990000;"><font size="3">Questions? Call:</font> </span><font size="4"><span style="font-weight: bold; color: #990000;">225-766-0050</span></font></p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style="font-weight: bold;">7301 Hennessy Blvd., Suite 200</span><br style="font-weight: bold;" />\r\n<span style="font-weight: bold;">Baton Rouge, LA 70808</span><br />\r\nWe are located in the Orthopedic Center, at the end of Hennessy Blvd, next to Our Lady of the Lake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our office is open Monday through Friday, 8:00 AM until 5:00 PM.<br />\r\nÂ </p>\r\n\r\n<h2>From the West:Â  <font size="2" style="font-weight: bold;">(Port Allen, Brusly, Plaquemine, New Roads, Lafayette)</font></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Proceed East on I-10 East through Baton Rouge to the I-10, I-12 split approximately 6.0 Miles from the Mississippi River Bridge</li>\r\n	<li>At the I-10, I-12 split stay in the right lanes to continue on I-10 East to New Orleans</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed approximately 1.1 miles and exit at Essen Lane - Exit 160 to the right (South) toward the hospital</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed 0.7 Miles South on Essen Lane to Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Turn right onto Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed West on Hennessy Blvd. for 5 blocks â€” end at 7301 Hennessyâ€”</li>\r\n	<li>the Orthopedic Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2><a classname="" href="" name="east" target=""></a>From the East:Â  <font size="2" style="font-weight: bold;">(Denham Springs, Walker, Hammond)</font></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Proceed West on I-12 West through Baton Rouge to the I-10, I-12 split approximately 9.4 miles from Denham Springs</li>\r\n	<li>Merge onto I-10 East via Exit 1A toward New Orleans</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed approximately 1.1 miles and Exit at Essen Lane - Exit 160 to the right (South) toward the hospital</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed 0.7 miles South on Essen Lane to Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Turn right onto Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed West on Hennessy Blvd. for 5 blocksâ€”end at 7301 Hennessyâ€”the Orthopedic Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2><a classname="" href="" name="north" target=""></a> From the North:Â  <font size="2" style="font-weight: bold;">(Baker, Zachary, Clinton, St. Francisville, Woodville, MS) </font></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Proceed South on I-110 South to I-10 East approximately 6.6 miles from the Harding Blvd. Exit (Baton Rouge Metropolitan Airport Exit) Stay in the left lane as approaching I-10.</li>\r\n	<li>Merge onto I-10 East via Exit 1I on the left toward New Orleans</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed East on I-10 East through Baton Rouge to the I-10, I-12 split approximately 5.3 miles</li>\r\n	<li>At the I-10, I-12 split stay in the right lanes to continue on I-10 East toward New Orleans</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed approximately 1.1 miles and Exit at Essen Lane - Exit 160 to the right (South) toward the hospital</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed 0.7 miles South on Essen Lane to Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Turn right onto Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed West on Hennessy Blvd. for 5 blocksâ€”end at 7301 Hennessyâ€”the Orthopedic Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h2><a classname="" href="" name="south" target=""></a>From the South:Â  <font size="2" style="font-weight: bold;">(Praireville, Gonzales, Gramercy, LaPlace, New Orleans) </font></h2>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Proceed West on I-10 West to the Baton Rouge Essen Lane Exit Approximately 5.7 miles from Highland Road Exit</li>\r\n	<li>Take the Essen Lane Exit 160 and turn left onto Essen Lane</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed 0.7 miles South on Essen Lane to Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Turn right onto Hennessy Blvd.</li>\r\n	<li>Proceed West on Hennessy Blvd. for 5 blocksâ€”end at 7301 Hennessyâ€”the Orthopedic Center</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', '2014-08-29 12:40:36');
